WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:54.720
[country music]

00:01:02.314 --> 00:01:05.332
[Peter] Doc, if the grid goes out
and everything stops…

00:01:05.332 --> 00:01:08.448
We're good. We could probably
hang out for at least two years.

00:01:08.448 --> 00:01:09.711
-Two years?
-Two years.

00:01:09.711 --> 00:01:13.737
So we're going to get into it today,
but this is sort of off-grid 2.0.

00:01:13.737 --> 00:01:15.675
-Right.
-You're not living in a cabin.

00:01:15.675 --> 00:01:17.311
You're living a modern day life.

00:01:17.311 --> 00:01:21.194
Live normal. Be on the grid.
Luxuries, Uber Eats, whatever you want.

00:01:21.194 --> 00:01:23.507
But at the same time
be able to flip a switch

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:25.418
and go off-grid if you need to.

00:01:26.137 --> 00:01:28.181
I'm trying to get away from gas.

00:01:28.589 --> 00:01:31.297
My chainsaw is electric.
The mower is electric.

00:01:31.297 --> 00:01:34.061
This cart is electric
even though I have gas.

00:01:34.061 --> 00:01:36.759
People think that
you have to own a hundred acres,

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:39.185
but we lived in neighborhoods
all of our life

00:01:39.502 --> 00:01:43.172
and I've always done this sort of
backup hybrid where I've been prepared.

00:01:43.435 --> 00:01:45.201
My motto is prep and forget.

00:01:45.201 --> 00:01:47.832
Go live your life and enjoy
because you're already prepared.

00:01:47.832 --> 00:01:51.468
You understand how little
you have to have to survive basically.

00:01:51.468 --> 00:01:53.226
Not survive, but to get by.

00:01:53.451 --> 00:01:54.860
Doc, one question here.

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:57.265
Someone's invading the property.
You get up there.

00:01:57.265 --> 00:01:59.212
-Sniper positions.
-Your sniper positions.

00:01:59.212 --> 00:02:02.643
So I've got four of these
all through behind the pond.

00:02:02.643 --> 00:02:04.978
We'll take a run back there
and take a look at that area,

00:02:04.978 --> 00:02:07.378
but we've got four of these
deer stands up here.

00:02:07.378 --> 00:02:09.394
-Oh, these are deer stands?
-These are deer stands.

00:02:09.394 --> 00:02:12.332
So every morning
during deer season I wake up at 4:30.

00:02:12.332 --> 00:02:13.954
I guess you call it deer hunting.

00:02:13.955 --> 00:02:15.748
For me, it's more deer watching.

00:02:15.748 --> 00:02:18.397
I mean, I don't…
we only take a couple deer the whole year,

00:02:18.397 --> 00:02:20.171
but I'll watch thousands come through here.

00:02:20.171 --> 00:02:21.703
There's Bubba. [laughs]

00:02:23.297 --> 00:02:27.061
He was mean to all the girls,
so he got kicked out of the chicken house.

00:02:27.061 --> 00:02:29.637
All these fields up here, it's a hybrid

00:02:29.637 --> 00:02:31.551
where they're all planted for the wildlife.

00:02:31.551 --> 00:02:35.019
You can see the feeders up here
and this is all planted for the wildlife,

00:02:35.019 --> 00:02:38.925
plus the chickens eat it, plus if you
ever want to come out here yourself…

00:02:40.314 --> 00:02:41.314
That's Kale.

00:02:42.070 --> 00:02:45.297
So if you want to eat kale,
you can get kale, radish, turnip,

00:02:45.297 --> 00:02:46.636
all these fields in here.

00:02:46.636 --> 00:02:49.506
In fact, there's a purple top turnip
up there that's that big.

00:02:49.507 --> 00:02:51.912
You can come out here
and eat any of this all winter long.

00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:57.441
[Doc laughs]

00:02:57.441 --> 00:02:58.678
[rooster crows]

00:02:59.054 --> 00:03:01.909
And that's one way I think
everyone can look at it, it's fun to do.

00:03:01.910 --> 00:03:05.719
Old school prepping,
it used to be about fear and anxiety.

00:03:06.031 --> 00:03:08.859
Now it's just you have fun with it
and you know you're prepared.

00:03:08.859 --> 00:03:10.060
Fear's not driving this?

00:03:10.060 --> 00:03:11.250
No, not at all.

00:03:11.743 --> 00:03:14.428
'Cause I'm done.
I have nothing to worry about anymore.

00:03:14.428 --> 00:03:17.912
This actually is what
the roads used to look like in 1855.

00:03:17.912 --> 00:03:19.530
This is what you traveled down.

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:21.125
-How many acres in total?

00:03:21.125 --> 00:03:22.335
Total of 40.

00:03:22.335 --> 00:03:25.605
So as an example, in 1996,

00:03:26.101 --> 00:03:29.586
Hurricane Fran hit us in Raleigh,
where we were living.

00:03:29.727 --> 00:03:31.747
We were without power for 12 days.

00:03:32.174 --> 00:03:35.404
I had my daughter
lying in front of my big fireplace

00:03:35.404 --> 00:03:37.819
'cause trees were falling down
all around our neighborhood.

00:03:37.819 --> 00:03:41.289
We woke up and half the houses
in my neighborhood were destroyed.

00:03:41.289 --> 00:03:42.740
No power for 12 days

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:44.838
and I wasn't prepared.

00:03:45.193 --> 00:03:49.222
That was sort of the thing to say,
we'll call it a gray swan event,

00:03:49.222 --> 00:03:53.121
where it's a possibility
but you don't take it seriously.

00:03:53.121 --> 00:03:54.190
You don't plan for it.

00:03:54.190 --> 00:03:56.340
I've been through five
different hurricanes.

00:03:57.131 --> 00:04:00.954
I've been through COVID.
I've been through 9-11.

00:04:00.954 --> 00:04:03.331
I mean at 63
you've been through enough crap

00:04:03.332 --> 00:04:05.446
where let's just prepare a little bit.

00:04:05.453 --> 00:04:06.866
-So this stuff marked you?

00:04:06.866 --> 00:04:09.647
-Yeah, absolutely.
It's just good life experience.

00:04:10.993 --> 00:04:11.993
[Doc chuckles]

00:04:12.377 --> 00:04:14.390
The guy that used to own this,

00:04:14.390 --> 00:04:16.940
he had goats out here
and I found that in the woods.

00:04:18.450 --> 00:04:20.586
I've worked since I was a teenager.

00:04:20.586 --> 00:04:22.470
I've worked for almost 50 years.

00:04:22.470 --> 00:04:26.873
And the last thing I want to do is retire
into a job that I have to work non-stop.

00:04:26.873 --> 00:04:29.313
True off-grid living? Dude, it's hard.

00:04:29.546 --> 00:04:31.605
I mean, it's a lot of work.

00:04:31.605 --> 00:04:34.236
I've seen a bit more of it
actually poking up

00:04:34.236 --> 00:04:36.484
where people live in a modern way.

00:04:36.484 --> 00:04:38.357
They're not in the middle of nowhere.

00:04:38.358 --> 00:04:40.180
You're what 25 minutes from the…

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:42.294
Major towns, major cities.

00:04:42.294 --> 00:04:44.944
If I want to go to Kroger
it's 25 minutes down the road.

00:04:44.944 --> 00:04:48.316
Home Depot, Lowe's,
it's all around me, medical centers.

00:04:48.316 --> 00:04:50.041
Do you think most of us are reactive.

00:04:50.049 --> 00:04:52.289
-You're taking a pro active approach.
-Yeah.

00:04:52.771 --> 00:04:55.357
I'm in the reactive.
If the grid goes down for three days,

00:04:55.813 --> 00:04:58.530
I mean I could maybe last a week.
I don't know. Right?

00:04:58.530 --> 00:05:01.926
The average…
90% of households in this country,

00:05:02.652 --> 00:05:06.055
after four days, five days,

00:05:06.055 --> 00:05:08.166
they pretty much
start to run out of everything.

00:05:08.166 --> 00:05:11.980
And what's interesting about that
is we don't learn.

00:05:12.774 --> 00:05:14.197
So we went through COVID

00:05:14.873 --> 00:05:17.058
and we just, we don't learn to prepare.

00:05:17.059 --> 00:05:20.472
And people can just do
a little bit of preparation work

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:22.802
and have seven to 14 days.

00:05:23.615 --> 00:05:26.138
That's all you need, really, in most cases.

00:05:26.572 --> 00:05:28.660
When we bought this,
you couldn't see the pond.

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:30.780
We took out about 20 trees here.

00:05:31.057 --> 00:05:34.695
Trees destroy your pond berm.
We had to take that down, rebuild that.

00:05:34.695 --> 00:05:37.137
And then this is just,
we've stocked it twice.

00:05:37.409 --> 00:05:40.113
We just… sort of a
recreational little fishing thing.

00:05:40.113 --> 00:05:41.848
-You're catching fish out of here?
-Oh yeah.

00:05:41.848 --> 00:05:44.382
I've caught nine pound bass out of here.

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:48.038
[Doc] So house,
we're going to go into at the end.

00:05:48.038 --> 00:05:50.551
-But you redid this completely, right?
-Right.

00:05:50.884 --> 00:05:53.965
To keep it family friendly,
I called it the crap hole

00:05:53.965 --> 00:05:56.234
because it was,
it was just a piece of crap.

00:05:56.622 --> 00:05:59.066
It was abandoned
for over a year and a half.

00:05:59.510 --> 00:06:01.381
The guy actually, who was in poor health

00:06:01.382 --> 00:06:04.462
actually died from COVID
and the family put it on the market.

00:06:04.462 --> 00:06:07.186
And thank goodness
this place was a disaster.

00:06:07.186 --> 00:06:10.015
You can maybe put up
a picture of what it looked like.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:14.341
It was just junk.
There was junk all through here.

00:06:14.341 --> 00:06:16.873
took a year
just to clean everything off of here.

00:06:17.356 --> 00:06:20.584
Now, I wanted to put
a little sort of guest cabin over here.

00:06:20.584 --> 00:06:23.139
So if my brother
wants to come up and deer hunt for a week

00:06:23.139 --> 00:06:27.422
or worst case scenario,
if the house were to burn down

00:06:27.422 --> 00:06:30.596
you could actually live over here
while you took care of your house.

00:06:30.596 --> 00:06:31.863
-You're married, Doc, right?

00:06:31.863 --> 00:06:34.634
Yeah. Older kids, they're gone, grandkids.

00:06:34.928 --> 00:06:36.522
When this got dropped in here,

00:06:36.522 --> 00:06:39.353
there was nothing but spray foam
and 2 x 4s on the inside.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:40.326
-Okay.

00:06:40.326 --> 00:06:42.326
And then we redid the whole thing.

00:06:42.326 --> 00:06:45.280
Security lock on every door I own.

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:47.240
-Ahhh. You did a great job.

00:06:47.240 --> 00:06:50.610
We got an air conditioning,
microwave, refrigerator. Look at the view.

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:54.780
-The view is… your artwork let's call it.
The solar panels.

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:57.945
And then this like 1840 table.

00:06:58.269 --> 00:06:59.845
Look the nails in it are all square.

00:06:59.845 --> 00:07:03.394
-It's a great fusion of rustic but modern.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:05.110
And that's kind of…

00:07:05.111 --> 00:07:08.204
I want luxury and I want nice,
but at the same time…

00:07:08.454 --> 00:07:10.612
-You want these old floors.

00:07:10.612 --> 00:07:11.612
-Right.

00:07:12.232 --> 00:07:13.240
What are these?

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:15.590
They're old spikes from plows.

00:07:15.590 --> 00:07:18.618
I just found them, I just loved them,
and I started buying them.

00:07:18.618 --> 00:07:20.459
And they just make
the coolest little accents.

00:07:20.459 --> 00:07:21.541
-They are cool.

00:07:21.541 --> 00:07:23.411
-This is sort of the brain center.

00:07:24.177 --> 00:07:26.440
We don't really have a good storage space.

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:27.746
-Of the whole operation?

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:29.626
Of the power station.

00:07:29.971 --> 00:07:31.968
This is the power station brain center.

00:07:31.968 --> 00:07:34.040
So this is your solar coming into here?

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:36.035
Solar comes into this battery system.

00:07:36.035 --> 00:07:40.693
This is the latest and greatest
DPUX from EcoFlow.

00:07:41.013 --> 00:07:43.756
I think it's better
for most people as it's portable.

00:07:43.756 --> 00:07:46.391
So if you ever move,
if you ever sell your house,

00:07:46.391 --> 00:07:48.368
you just load this up
and take it with you.

00:07:48.368 --> 00:07:49.934
This is 12,000 watts,

00:07:50.209 --> 00:07:52.188
6,000 watt hours per battery.

00:07:52.188 --> 00:07:54.644
That's 60,000 watt hours of storage.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:58.288
And then this drives
12,000 watts over to the house.

00:07:58.288 --> 00:08:00.933
I have a 2-2-2-4 huge electric cable

00:08:00.933 --> 00:08:03.094
that runs underground
back over to the house.

00:08:03.094 --> 00:08:03.816
Okay.

00:08:03.816 --> 00:08:05.958
And I'll show you the switch over there.

00:08:06.398 --> 00:08:08.404
This actually from…

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:10.513
I don't understand this world at all.

00:08:10.513 --> 00:08:12.099
It looks quite simple.

00:08:12.412 --> 00:08:17.181
It's very simple and that's why more
and more people are going to this system

00:08:17.703 --> 00:08:20.645
versus you can do a DIY solar system

00:08:20.645 --> 00:08:23.720
with your inverters
and your batteries and your wiring.

00:08:23.720 --> 00:08:27.307
Probably for maybe
half the price of this

00:08:27.308 --> 00:08:28.961
or not maybe half.

00:08:28.961 --> 00:08:30.920
But the simplicity of this,

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:32.344
you put it together,

00:08:32.817 --> 00:08:34.520
You can start with two batteries.

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:36.400
-Just do two batteries.
-Yep.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:40.053
Just do two batteries. It's on wheels,
and plug it in, you back up to your house.

00:08:40.430 --> 00:08:44.691
I'll show you over here. I have a $100
battery system with a little solar panel.

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:47.457
If you want to go this
with the solar panels,

00:08:47.457 --> 00:08:50.010
you're going to dump $35,000 into it.

00:08:50.710 --> 00:08:52.738
-For all of this?
-All this and that.

00:08:53.033 --> 00:08:54.265
-And the panels?
-Yep.

00:08:55.383 --> 00:08:57.452
With this system because it's modular,

00:08:57.452 --> 00:08:59.112
you can start off with the…

00:08:59.892 --> 00:09:02.405
The main head
and two batteries you can start off,

00:09:02.405 --> 00:09:06.027
I think it's about $7,000
for two batteries.

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:09.720
And then you just keep
adding batteries, and you bump it up.

00:09:09.980 --> 00:09:13.223
Solar panels really
are not that expensive to be honest.

00:09:13.223 --> 00:09:14.668
I thought it would be so much more.

00:09:14.668 --> 00:09:16.909
People think it's gonna be
$80,000 to $100,000.

00:09:16.909 --> 00:09:20.041
And that's when you have
a company come out and do the installation.

00:09:20.041 --> 00:09:21.376
-You did this?
-Right.

00:09:22.299 --> 00:09:24.660
-Okay.
-Matter of fact, if you come over here,

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:28.723
you can see we didn't spend a whole bunch
of money on the solar racks over here.

00:09:28.723 --> 00:09:29.979
-That's pretty straightforward.

00:09:29.979 --> 00:09:32.729
-Yep.
It's a four by four system with these.

00:09:32.950 --> 00:09:35.640
These things are cheap and it's just…

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:39.502
-And they don't have to be straight.
They can be on a slope like this.

00:09:39.502 --> 00:09:42.920
They're on a slope and they're not perfect.
They're a little bit not aligned.

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:46.289
But Jesse, my guy, and I
came over here and did this in two days

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:48.813
and put up the panels and wired it up.

00:09:48.814 --> 00:09:51.770
And is it really professional looking?

00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:53.056
No, but it works.

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:55.766
When it comes to water,

00:09:56.644 --> 00:09:58.161
we have multiple sources.

00:09:58.161 --> 00:10:00.833
So the pond is actually
spring fed from over here.

00:10:01.161 --> 00:10:03.743
This is the original
shallow well from the house

00:10:03.743 --> 00:10:05.719
that served the house for 30 years.

00:10:06.366 --> 00:10:09.993
You can't really see it right now
because it's covered with insulation.

00:10:09.993 --> 00:10:13.467
But it's just a 30 inch wide
by 30 feet deep.

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:15.690
That's all you have to go down here,
30 feet?

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:18.040
Almost all your shallow wells
are done this way.

00:10:18.646 --> 00:10:20.413
The problem with shallow wells is

00:10:20.414 --> 00:10:23.178
they pick up everything that's bad
from around here.

00:10:23.372 --> 00:10:24.068
Okay.

00:10:24.068 --> 00:10:27.088
And they have a tendency to
really have a lot of bacteria.

00:10:27.487 --> 00:10:30.528
I run my irrigation systems
off of it in my hose now.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:33.620
-We don't use it for the house.
-What about your drinking water?

00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:36.035
We'll go up here
and I'll show you that system.

00:10:36.035 --> 00:10:38.098
This is where
you better have a checkbook ready

00:10:38.098 --> 00:10:40.351
because the septic system back here

00:10:40.964 --> 00:10:42.940
was actually concrete, the tubes.

00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:43.940
Okay.

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:45.734
We had to put in a brand new septic system.

00:10:45.734 --> 00:10:49.680
Okay, now you're dropping 15 grand
on a new septic system and leach field.

00:10:50.146 --> 00:10:51.278
You need a well.

00:10:51.278 --> 00:10:54.789
Well, you've got to drill down
for a deep well for clean water,

00:10:54.789 --> 00:10:56.239
you've got to drill 600 feet.

00:10:57.355 --> 00:10:58.485
You've got 600 feet.

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:01.358
Your new well is going to pop you 20 grand.

00:11:01.358 --> 00:11:04.296
That's clean water, no filtration.

00:11:04.296 --> 00:11:07.177
You can literally drink it.
It smells like rock.

00:11:07.177 --> 00:11:10.236
It has kind of a sulfur rock
'cause it's coming through the granite.

00:11:10.236 --> 00:11:12.448
-Okay.
-But it's super, super clean water.

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:13.901
Now, what I do,

00:11:14.416 --> 00:11:16.611
it gets a little bit confusing here, but

00:11:17.477 --> 00:11:21.259
inside here I have
a multistage filtration system.

00:11:21.873 --> 00:11:22.873
So…

00:11:25.019 --> 00:11:27.126
-Do you have a homeless guy living here?

00:11:27.126 --> 00:11:29.760
That is the pressure tank.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:31.450
-Okay.
-And I keep for freezing.

00:11:31.932 --> 00:11:35.829
And it keeps it cold
in the summertime and warm in the winter.

00:11:36.356 --> 00:11:38.996
But the well comes up here.
It goes through a pre-filter.

00:11:39.450 --> 00:11:41.340
Then it goes through a carbonized filter.

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:42.940
Then it goes to a post-filter.

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:44.820
And then it goes to this UV filter.

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:47.284
And the UV kills
any kind of thing that's living,

00:11:47.284 --> 00:11:48.780
like viruses or whatever.

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:50.074
Then it goes to the house.

00:11:50.074 --> 00:11:52.898
-Is it stripping of all its minerals?
-No.

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:55.447
It's still, it's still very mineral.

00:11:55.447 --> 00:11:58.346
Matter of fact, that's one of the problems
with wells like this

00:11:58.759 --> 00:12:01.026
is you pull up a whole bunch of calcium.

00:12:01.026 --> 00:12:03.270
And so you have to
constantly clean your shower

00:12:03.270 --> 00:12:04.950
'cause you have those hard water spots.

00:12:04.950 --> 00:12:07.620
-So this, you said
it was 20 G to put this in?

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:11.679
You're dropping 20 G in any well out here
that's about 600 feet.

00:12:12.327 --> 00:12:14.054
'Cause that's just…

00:12:14.054 --> 00:12:16.756
-So yeah, I wasn't even thinking of water.

00:12:17.313 --> 00:12:20.446
Most people don't
because they're on city water.

00:12:20.446 --> 00:12:22.611
-So you, you're purely on your own well.

00:12:23.038 --> 00:12:24.038
Yes.

00:12:24.038 --> 00:12:26.990
-How do you know
that's gonna be good five, 10 years out?

00:12:26.990 --> 00:12:29.931
Because what we did
is we put in a backup well.

00:12:31.160 --> 00:12:33.665
-So behind my…
-Of course you did.

00:12:33.883 --> 00:12:36.247
-Behind, see that little yellow shack?
-Okay.

00:12:36.247 --> 00:12:38.613
-In between the container and whatever?
-Yeah.

00:12:38.613 --> 00:12:40.330
That's another 600 foot well.

00:12:41.030 --> 00:12:43.693
So I had them drill a backup well
because here's the problem.

00:12:43.693 --> 00:12:44.806
People don't understand.

00:12:44.806 --> 00:12:46.189
If this goes bad,

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:50.154
I may be a month without it trying
to get a guy out here to fix this thing.

00:12:50.154 --> 00:12:51.665
-Okay. So rookie question.

00:12:51.665 --> 00:12:54.534
Doc, you have a well here.
You have a well not far away.

00:12:54.813 --> 00:12:56.905
Isn't it pulling from
pretty much the same place?

00:12:56.905 --> 00:12:58.649
No,
because when you go through,

00:12:58.649 --> 00:13:01.620
it's basically you're drilling
through cracks in the rock.

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:02.416
-Okay.

00:13:02.416 --> 00:13:04.262
And you get different water rates.

00:13:04.262 --> 00:13:06.000
It's weird how it works.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.790
It's basically
you're pulling from different cracks.

00:13:08.790 --> 00:13:11.886
So if this one, main thing is
what happens if this pump fails

00:13:12.476 --> 00:13:15.943
and you're a week without water
'cause the guy can't come out and fix it.

00:13:15.943 --> 00:13:18.995
All I have to do now
is there's a switch in here.

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:23.687
I flip the switch and that well actually
feeds all the way down here to this.

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:26.715
And now that well feeds
the house through that system.

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:32.586
You can do something like this
very reasonable

00:13:32.586 --> 00:13:36.039
if you just buy a few acres
and you just keep it pretty modest.

00:13:36.338 --> 00:13:40.744
Yes, I spent a lot of money,
but my wife and I live very modestly.

00:13:41.510 --> 00:13:43.719
I can tell you how many times
we've been out to eat

00:13:43.719 --> 00:13:46.020
in the past 10 years,
probably on two hands.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:47.065
-Seriously?

00:13:47.065 --> 00:13:50.240
We don't go out to eat. We don't travel.
We don't drink. We don't do drugs.

00:13:50.241 --> 00:13:51.639
-No date nights?

00:13:51.639 --> 00:13:56.096
No, we're very much
homebodies and I worked,

00:13:56.829 --> 00:14:00.635
gosh, the past 10 years, I worked
seven days a week, 10 to 12 hours a day.

00:14:00.635 --> 00:14:02.739
-What were you in?
-Just whatever.

00:14:02.739 --> 00:14:05.081
-Okay.
-I was an entrepreneur my whole life.

00:14:05.548 --> 00:14:07.518
-Okay.
-So I've always been an entrepreneur.

00:14:07.518 --> 00:14:10.073
Ups and downs.
That's part of the experience of

00:14:10.535 --> 00:14:11.835
getting your butt whipped,

00:14:12.471 --> 00:14:14.525
losing everything and having to rebuild.

00:14:14.525 --> 00:14:16.188
Lose everything, having to rebuild.

00:14:16.188 --> 00:14:17.670
It's that life experience.

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:18.910
It's the same thing.

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:20.160
Going through hurricanes.

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:21.490
Going through COVID.

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:24.966
Unfortunately, we're in a society
that doesn't learn a whole lot. [chuckles]

00:14:24.966 --> 00:14:26.760
We don't learn from the past lessons.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:28.215
We forget very easily.

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:31.363
-You come to tell me we're not
having the conversations about COVID

00:14:31.363 --> 00:14:33.432
and like what we could do
different next time?

00:14:33.432 --> 00:14:34.085
Yeah.

00:14:34.085 --> 00:14:36.780
Those aren't really creeping up
in society so much?

00:14:36.780 --> 00:14:38.227
Let's forget it, right?

00:14:38.227 --> 00:14:40.064
Yeah, it's over. Forget about it.

00:14:40.064 --> 00:14:42.266
But I think that's just a way of the mind

00:14:42.267 --> 00:14:44.619
wanting to like get rid of
anything that's negative,

00:14:44.626 --> 00:14:48.174
purge the negative, move forward,
be optimistic about tomorrow.

00:14:48.383 --> 00:14:50.018
And you need to have a balance, right?

00:14:50.018 --> 00:14:52.784
Because you don't want to
constantly be in this prepper state

00:14:53.270 --> 00:14:55.196
'cause then you're
waiting for the apocalypse.

00:14:55.196 --> 00:14:58.251
Yes. You're walking around
with an AR, bulletproof vest,

00:14:58.697 --> 00:15:02.610
and camouflage,
and that's old school prepping.

00:15:02.610 --> 00:15:04.982
There was a show on called…

00:15:05.509 --> 00:15:09.160
Doomsday Preppers
that used to be on Discovery or something.

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:09.852
-Yeah.

00:15:09.852 --> 00:15:11.935
That is gone where this is what it is.

00:15:12.283 --> 00:15:13.413
You prep and forget.

00:15:13.413 --> 00:15:16.248
-Okay. One thing about the prepper,
like the true preppers,

00:15:16.248 --> 00:15:19.347
whenever I come into them
or seen them on videos,

00:15:19.607 --> 00:15:21.214
they don't look that happy.

00:15:21.214 --> 00:15:23.019
It doesn't look like that much fun.

00:15:23.019 --> 00:15:24.569
-They're always worried.
-Right?

00:15:24.990 --> 00:15:28.220
And I do feel too,
if you're the prepped guy,

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:30.720
you're doing the bunker
in New Zealand or wherever.

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:32.870
Some of the oligarchs
are doing that, right?

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:36.593
It's like almost you're a target
because your security eventually

00:15:36.593 --> 00:15:38.706
is going to have more fealty
towards their family.

00:15:38.706 --> 00:15:39.561
-Right?
-Right.

00:15:39.561 --> 00:15:42.478
And you're like
that's the guy with resources

00:15:42.711 --> 00:15:44.462
and everyone goes for that guy.

00:15:44.462 --> 00:15:45.775
And I have…

00:15:47.282 --> 00:15:49.412
I guess you could take it
to whatever level you want.

00:15:49.412 --> 00:15:52.249
So if you're talking about
hurricanes and thunderstorms

00:15:52.249 --> 00:15:53.661
and something like a COVID,

00:15:53.943 --> 00:15:55.493
you're not going to have people

00:15:56.092 --> 00:15:59.679
coming out here
hunting for your food type deal.

00:15:59.973 --> 00:16:02.999
If you're talking about
like an EMP or solar flare

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:04.956
grid down on large scale,

00:16:05.268 --> 00:16:06.921
that's when you got to worry about it.

00:16:06.921 --> 00:16:10.868
There are physical things we've done
out here that I won't talk about. [laughs]

00:16:10.868 --> 00:16:12.180
-You got booby traps?

00:16:12.180 --> 00:16:13.451
No, not booby traps.

00:16:13.451 --> 00:16:15.883
But being an old Marine,

00:16:16.566 --> 00:16:19.752
I sort of look at this strategically,
and if you'll notice,

00:16:19.752 --> 00:16:23.498
you can't access my house
without an open area in between.

00:16:23.498 --> 00:16:25.409
-So I can see…
-You thought this out?

00:16:25.409 --> 00:16:28.447
Yeah. We took out,
we opened up the area all in between

00:16:28.714 --> 00:16:31.118
just so I could have clear view
of what's coming.

00:16:31.118 --> 00:16:34.223
And just to open it up too for,
you know,

00:16:34.223 --> 00:16:36.913
sunlight and everything else
and trees falling on the house.

00:16:36.913 --> 00:16:39.345
But it's just something
that you just think about is

00:16:39.345 --> 00:16:42.125
you got 80 yards
worth of open area all around.

00:16:42.510 --> 00:16:44.160
-So you were in the Marines?
-Yes.

00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:46.130
-So you have the skills?
-Yes.

00:16:46.130 --> 00:16:47.680
And you know how to fire a gun?

00:16:49.491 --> 00:16:53.151
If you're up in that field
and you're trying to hurt me or my family,

00:16:53.548 --> 00:16:55.116
it doesn't matter how far away you are.

00:16:55.116 --> 00:16:57.947
-What kind of arsenal do you have?
-I'll show you a couple of them.

00:16:58.220 --> 00:17:00.526
Out here, everyone has
sort of the same thing.

00:17:00.526 --> 00:17:01.626
We have

00:17:02.166 --> 00:17:04.786
handguns, we have hunting rifles,

00:17:04.786 --> 00:17:07.680
and then we usually have
plinking rifles, like ARs or something.

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:08.873
I'll show you that.

00:17:08.873 --> 00:17:10.676
But like in my cart right now,

00:17:10.676 --> 00:17:13.758
everywhere I go, there's a 9 millimeter
within 10 feet of me.

00:17:13.758 --> 00:17:15.142
-Seriously?
-If it's not on my hip.

00:17:15.149 --> 00:17:17.401
-There's one right there.
-Are you worried or something?

00:17:17.401 --> 00:17:18.401
No.

00:17:18.408 --> 00:17:21.688
I had two coyotes up in my field.

00:17:21.981 --> 00:17:25.131
If it's up here and they're trying to
get into my chicken house,

00:17:25.748 --> 00:17:26.748
that's the main thing.

00:17:26.748 --> 00:17:29.041
I got you. Don't mess with the chickens.

