[latch clanks and opens]

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:07.600
Kind of dark in here, but this is
at least a whole winter's worth,

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:10.000
if not one and a half
winter's worth of firewood.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:11.847
I have all my chicken feed.

00:19:12.520 --> 00:19:14.400
Corn for the deer.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:16.094
-So you're doing wood heat?

00:19:16.094 --> 00:19:17.370
Just supplemental.

00:19:18.007 --> 00:19:19.994
I have a five-ton Trane heat pump,

00:19:20.527 --> 00:19:21.527
but…

00:19:21.933 --> 00:19:25.215
my wife always complains 'cause she's hot,
so I get near the wood stove.

00:19:25.215 --> 00:19:28.033
You'll see my Vermont casting stove.
I'll have it going.

00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:31.493
-Yeah, I grew up in Vermont,
so that wood would last you like…

00:19:31.493 --> 00:19:33.279
-A couple weeks.
-A couple weeks.

00:19:33.279 --> 00:19:34.279
So here

00:19:35.325 --> 00:19:39.139
on the barn, there's solar panels
up here we just put on.

00:19:39.530 --> 00:19:41.030
-Is this good here, Doc?
-Yeah.

00:19:41.733 --> 00:19:43.351
So we just put those up.

00:19:43.351 --> 00:19:45.901
And they're not that strong.
They're old ones I had.

00:19:47.851 --> 00:19:48.877
Here's a good example.

00:19:48.877 --> 00:19:52.278
Here's a backup battery system,
kind of like that one.

00:19:52.278 --> 00:19:55.124
If you just get this one, 1,600 bucks.

00:19:55.694 --> 00:19:56.755
-That's it?

00:19:56.755 --> 00:19:58.180
That's it. 1,600 bucks.

00:19:58.180 --> 00:20:00.266
That puts off 6,000 watts.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:04.653
So this whole place is, if I want to,
I could just off-grid this whole place.

00:20:04.653 --> 00:20:08.689
And you've mentioned you make videos,
and I want to let the audience know,

00:20:08.689 --> 00:20:10.440
Doc is also a YouTuber.

00:20:10.440 --> 00:20:12.952
Has quite a collection of videos.

00:20:13.186 --> 00:20:15.506
From this type of stuff, to lawn care…

00:20:15.506 --> 00:20:17.900
Gardening, you name it, how-to…

00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:21.283
Ultimate polymath,
Doc does everything, renaissance man.

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:23.625
I'm going to leave Doc's link down below.

00:20:23.625 --> 00:20:24.958
What's a really…

00:20:24.958 --> 00:20:25.958
[rooster crows]

00:20:27.124 --> 00:20:29.268
[Peter] You guys have
a twisted relationship, huh?

00:20:29.268 --> 00:20:31.033
He's so weird.

00:20:31.033 --> 00:20:33.233
Now,
I did something really cool that I think

00:20:33.861 --> 00:20:36.281
your viewers
will actually find interesting.

00:20:37.535 --> 00:20:39.491
AI is eventually going to kill us.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:42.168
But at the same time,
you need to get into it.

00:20:42.168 --> 00:20:43.028
You need to use it.

00:20:43.028 --> 00:20:45.884
Because, especially if you want to do
this kind of prepping stuff,

00:20:45.884 --> 00:20:48.559
you can take a picture
of your solar panel label

00:20:48.559 --> 00:20:50.894
and ask AI, say, "How do I hook this up?"

00:20:51.380 --> 00:20:52.580
"How do I hook this up?"

00:20:53.187 --> 00:20:55.580
And what are the voltage requirements?

00:20:55.580 --> 00:20:57.158
It's an amazing tool

00:20:57.159 --> 00:20:59.909
for if you want to be prepared
or do that kind of stuff.

00:21:01.280 --> 00:21:03.985
-Bubba, what are you doing, buddy?
-Bubba's sort of like a dog, huh?

00:21:03.985 --> 00:21:06.506
He's just like a dog, man.
He just follows me around.

00:21:06.506 --> 00:21:07.506
-Does Bubba peck?

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:10.119
He doesn't like to be touched.

00:21:10.119 --> 00:21:13.319
But when he goes like this,
he'll lean up against you like a dog.

00:21:13.319 --> 00:21:16.837
Okay, Doc, you're worried about AI.
You think it's going to ruin us completely.

00:21:16.837 --> 00:21:18.762
Oh, it is going to ruin us
completely eventually.

00:21:18.762 --> 00:21:22.201
But in the meantime,
it's one of the greatest tools you can use.

00:21:22.201 --> 00:21:24.044
So we have a nice window
is what you're saying?

00:21:24.044 --> 00:21:27.056
Yeah. So what I did was
I built a page on my website.

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:30.523
And what people can do,
I just posted a video.

00:21:30.523 --> 00:21:31.680
They go there,

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:33.448
if you go put your street…

00:21:33.448 --> 00:21:34.448
-Uh-huh.

00:21:34.674 --> 00:21:35.994
Your city and state,

00:21:36.841 --> 00:21:40.761
the AI agent on there
will do an evaluation of your area.

00:21:41.550 --> 00:21:43.748
And it will tell you
what are the threats,

00:21:43.748 --> 00:21:46.731
what's your problem
when the grid goes down on day…

00:21:46.731 --> 00:21:49.181
And it will describe
what happens day 1 through 3,

00:21:49.722 --> 00:21:51.957
day 7, day 15 and day 30.

00:21:52.460 --> 00:21:54.563
And it gives people a view

00:21:55.056 --> 00:21:58.093
what would happen
if the supply chain and grid went down.

00:21:58.093 --> 00:22:00.166
It's actually a really cool little tool.

00:22:00.173 --> 00:22:02.800
In a city, 72 hours, pure chaos, right?

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:04.576
Yes. Three or four days.

00:22:04.795 --> 00:22:05.795
If you're in a city,

00:22:06.710 --> 00:22:09.251
you need to figure a way to get out.
[chuckles]

00:22:09.980 --> 00:22:11.972
This wasn't here, obviously.

00:22:14.578 --> 00:22:17.900
The guys that put this up,
put this building up in six hours.

00:22:18.210 --> 00:22:19.410
-Were they Amish?

00:22:19.410 --> 00:22:22.042
-No, they were Mexican.
-[laughter]

00:22:23.095 --> 00:22:24.095
Close enough.

00:22:24.095 --> 00:22:26.355
-Six hours they put this up?
-Six hours.

00:22:26.355 --> 00:22:28.240
It's just like a kit barn or something?

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:30.410
They spec it out,
they build it at the factory,

00:22:30.410 --> 00:22:31.773
they bring it out and put it in.

00:22:31.774 --> 00:22:32.774
It was crazy.

00:22:32.774 --> 00:22:34.653
-What's the price of a barn like this?

00:22:34.653 --> 00:22:37.110
This thing will run you about eight grand.

00:22:37.537 --> 00:22:41.298
The foundation costs just as much.
When you have a cement thing poured.

00:22:41.298 --> 00:22:43.808
So you got about
eight grand in your cement,

00:22:43.808 --> 00:22:47.472
eight grand in the building,
but as you can see, desperately needed.

00:22:47.879 --> 00:22:51.565
This automatically plants,
cuts into the ground and seeds the corn.

00:22:51.565 --> 00:22:54.090
So we do use this for corn planting.

00:22:54.091 --> 00:22:57.347
Do you… [rooster crows]

00:22:57.348 --> 00:22:59.460
Do you think like 20 years out,

00:22:59.907 --> 00:23:01.541
hopefully you're in great shape then,

00:23:02.128 --> 00:23:04.207
but when you can no longer do this stuff?

00:23:04.207 --> 00:23:06.900
That's the whole point of this is…

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:10.977
I don't think my kids want this place.

00:23:10.977 --> 00:23:14.107
They're not willing to work
hard enough to maintain it.

00:23:14.107 --> 00:23:17.811
So I'll eventually, when I decide,
I get to a point where I say,

00:23:17.812 --> 00:23:19.799
"Hey, I can't do this anymore."

00:23:20.115 --> 00:23:23.499
Then what I'll do is I'll probably
just end up selling the place. So…

00:23:24.466 --> 00:23:28.620
But no, I don't think the kids would want
to come out here and work this hard.

00:23:28.621 --> 00:23:29.712
What do they think?

00:23:29.712 --> 00:23:31.708
What do family members, old friends,

00:23:31.709 --> 00:23:33.694
do they think Doc
lost his mind a little bit?

00:23:33.694 --> 00:23:35.268
Oh, no, 'cause I mean,

00:23:35.628 --> 00:23:38.477
actually my son,
after he graduated from college,

00:23:38.478 --> 00:23:41.274
spent a year out here
helping me, took a year off.

00:23:41.274 --> 00:23:43.025
Everybody that comes out here loves it.

00:23:43.025 --> 00:23:45.980
Grandkids will come out,
they'll feed the chickens and…

00:23:46.290 --> 00:23:47.490
[chickens clucking]

00:23:49.700 --> 00:23:53.714
I get 32 eggs a day right now
and it'll probably go up from there.

00:23:53.714 --> 00:23:55.089
-32 a day?
-A day.

00:23:55.089 --> 00:23:56.415
How many are you eating?

00:23:56.415 --> 00:23:58.478
-Just a handful. I give away the rest.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:02.953
I give away dozens and dozens of eggs
to all my neighbors, everyone.

00:24:09.359 --> 00:24:11.957
-This is my scratch grain that they eat.
-Okay.

00:24:12.563 --> 00:24:15.176
These are the Black fly larvae.

00:24:15.680 --> 00:24:17.353
And then they have chicken crumbles.

00:24:17.353 --> 00:24:19.420
The larvae's really good
with nutrients or what's…

00:24:19.421 --> 00:24:21.190
Yeah, protein, calcium,

00:24:21.191 --> 00:24:24.400
basically supplements where
they would normally be digging up worms.

00:24:24.400 --> 00:24:28.030
It's also important,
I think, to have greens.

00:24:28.263 --> 00:24:30.989
Since I can't free range out here
because of predators,

00:24:31.462 --> 00:24:34.581
I'll come out here and I'll pick…
maybe we'll do it a little bit later.

00:24:34.581 --> 00:24:36.704
I'll pick some turnips and radishes.

00:24:36.704 --> 00:24:39.417
If I throw them in here it's like piranhas.

00:24:39.417 --> 00:24:42.388
They just come attack them.
They just absolutely love them.

00:24:42.388 --> 00:24:46.238
You can see some of the old root stuff
in here where they've been eating them.

00:24:50.900 --> 00:24:52.240
I grabbed a video clip,

00:24:52.520 --> 00:24:55.328
maybe wifey can put it up
since she's your head editor,

00:24:55.752 --> 00:24:59.561
of it shows the tomatoes out here,
all the tomatoes.

00:24:59.561 --> 00:25:02.810
We had a thousand tomatoes
that we harvested from the vines.

00:25:02.810 --> 00:25:04.882
This garden, when it was all here,

00:25:04.882 --> 00:25:08.860
one year we got close to 3,000 pounds
of produce out of this one garden.

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:12.850
And that's everything from zucchinis,
to cucumbers, to tomatoes, to peppers.

00:25:12.850 --> 00:25:14.604
I had pepper plants out here.

00:25:14.905 --> 00:25:18.132
I know I had
250 red and green peppers at one point.

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:20.587
We'll just show the food area.

00:25:20.587 --> 00:25:23.950
But you can see
that's not that much of an area.

00:25:23.950 --> 00:25:26.233
So if someone had maybe half an acre

00:25:26.807 --> 00:25:29.628
at the old house where we were
I had a huge amount of produce

00:25:29.628 --> 00:25:31.155
and we only had half an acre.

00:25:31.430 --> 00:25:33.849
So people can put in
a garden in their backyard.

00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:37.004
What's the minimal amount you need

00:25:37.005 --> 00:25:39.445
to be somewhat this off-grid,

00:25:40.219 --> 00:25:41.376
be on solar,

00:25:41.872 --> 00:25:43.743
let's just say grow your own food,

00:25:43.743 --> 00:25:45.536
your vegetables, your chickens at least?

00:25:45.536 --> 00:25:46.700
There's a guy…

00:25:46.700 --> 00:25:49.418
There's a YouTuber online
and I think they do it on like…

00:25:49.418 --> 00:25:52.680
They grow tons of produce
and they're on like two acres.

00:25:52.680 --> 00:25:55.765
So you think two acres
would be the good bare minimum.

00:25:55.982 --> 00:25:57.728
If you do nothing but grass obviously

00:25:57.729 --> 00:26:00.206
and have a little garden
then it's not gonna work.

00:26:00.206 --> 00:26:03.756
But if you decide to actually
take a big portion of that yard and do…

00:26:03.756 --> 00:26:06.642
-It doesn't take much.
-What's two acres in this part of Georgia?

00:26:07.319 --> 00:26:08.626
It depends. Uh…

00:26:09.330 --> 00:26:11.719
Right now,
housing and land is so screwed up.

00:26:11.719 --> 00:26:14.466
But you could probably go
a little more rural and probably pick it up

00:26:14.472 --> 00:26:16.611
for probably $10,000 an acre.

00:26:17.105 --> 00:26:18.564
Okay. So 20 grand.

00:26:18.564 --> 00:26:21.199
What do you think? You set up a small home.

00:26:21.755 --> 00:26:25.715
I mean, these are all rough numbers,
but let's set a minimalistic setup.

00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:28.422
Your home is 1,500 square feet.

00:26:28.906 --> 00:26:31.806
Simple, straightforward, the whole shebang.

00:26:31.806 --> 00:26:33.506
What do you think that would cost?

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:35.880
God,
what an impossible number to come up with.

00:26:35.880 --> 00:26:37.863
I'll tell you what I would prefer to do.

00:26:37.863 --> 00:26:39.384
What I prefer to do is find…

00:26:39.846 --> 00:26:43.746
is to find an old house just like I did.

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:46.455
Find a piece of crap house
that has the infrastructure.

00:26:46.455 --> 00:26:49.700
So you don't have to pay for power lines
to be run. That's real expensive.

00:26:49.700 --> 00:26:51.964
You don't have to pay for your septic.
That's already in.

00:26:51.964 --> 00:26:53.005
Your well's already in.

00:26:53.005 --> 00:26:55.360
You just need to go in
and fix up the house.

00:26:55.360 --> 00:26:56.720
That's the ideal situation.

00:26:56.721 --> 00:26:58.747
But you've got to be a do-it-yourselfer.

00:26:59.659 --> 00:27:01.794
True, but I didn't do that.

00:27:01.794 --> 00:27:04.580
I hired a great contractor
to do that whole house.

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:06.875
-And when you say
that's going to be a bit confusing

00:27:06.875 --> 00:27:09.278
'cause we haven't talked about it,
but you're on solar.

00:27:09.279 --> 00:27:11.630
-But you're also tapped into the grid.
-Yeah.

00:27:11.630 --> 00:27:14.730
That's your setup
because during normal times…

00:27:14.730 --> 00:27:17.366
-We just live a normal life.
-It's just easier to do it that way?

00:27:17.366 --> 00:27:19.620
-Yeah.
-Why not go off your solar completely?

00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:22.160
I don't know.
I don't have to worry about it.

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:24.812
A lot of times
when you do have a solar system,

00:27:25.207 --> 00:27:27.034
you do have to sort of think a little bit

00:27:27.034 --> 00:27:28.260
because you don't want to run…

00:27:28.261 --> 00:27:30.619
[rooster crows]

00:27:30.965 --> 00:27:34.764
You don't want to be running
your dryer and your dishwasher

00:27:34.764 --> 00:27:37.351
and the oven all at the same time.

00:27:37.351 --> 00:27:40.576
You've got to be doing that during the day
when there's solar really.

00:27:40.576 --> 00:27:43.557
That's what you want.
I just don't want to think about that.

00:27:43.557 --> 00:27:45.772
And my power out here
is not that expensive.

00:27:45.772 --> 00:27:48.125
The whole place, I pay about $300 a month.

00:27:48.630 --> 00:27:52.433
So for me, it's more of it's a backup.

00:27:56.098 --> 00:27:57.555
[Doc] I've got a back loop here.

00:27:57.555 --> 00:28:01.042
This is the back 20 acres of my property
that's pretty secluded.

00:28:01.450 --> 00:28:03.947
I pretty much every day during deer season,

00:28:04.261 --> 00:28:06.168
it's kind of my retirement religion,

00:28:06.909 --> 00:28:10.153
I get up in the deer stand
and I'm not really deer hunting.

00:28:10.153 --> 00:28:11.220
I'm deer watching.

00:28:11.220 --> 00:28:15.511
And I just enjoy a couple of hours
by myself up in one of these stands.

00:28:15.905 --> 00:28:18.479
-So you're basically
a 12-year-old at this point, Doc.

00:28:18.479 --> 00:28:20.280
-Yeah.
-You've got forts out here.

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:22.263
-You're hanging out in your tent.
-[Doc chuckles]

00:28:22.330 --> 00:28:26.626
That's probably 30 years old,
that little deer stand or something.

00:28:26.626 --> 00:28:29.100
-You just stand up there?
-That's the way they used to hunt.

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:30.643
No. That's just… That's been here.

00:28:31.080 --> 00:28:33.583
What we built,
we call them our redneck skyscrapers.

00:28:33.583 --> 00:28:34.583
[laughter]

00:28:35.483 --> 00:28:39.036
Oh, that door's open. I've gotta go
close that door otherwise it'll rot.

00:28:39.036 --> 00:28:40.360
Got to clean up all the trash.

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:41.360
-What is this?

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:42.640
-Doe pee..

00:28:43.430 --> 00:28:45.800
-Can I check it out up there, Doc?
-Yeah. Sure.

00:28:45.800 --> 00:28:47.950
Let me have you hold the camera right here.

00:28:50.427 --> 00:28:51.520
[Peter] Okay. So…

00:28:51.980 --> 00:28:53.950
[Doc] Let's see how athletic he is.

00:28:53.950 --> 00:28:55.407
-You just go up here, Doc.

00:28:55.407 --> 00:28:58.107
There's some handles
to get up in there, so be careful.

00:29:01.292 --> 00:29:03.009
And then you're just sitting up here?

00:29:03.009 --> 00:29:05.761
-Yeah. You would turn around,
and you'd look out the back over there,

00:29:05.761 --> 00:29:07.411
and that's where you're watching.

00:29:08.263 --> 00:29:10.313
-Oh, let me see. I'll bring the camera up.

00:29:11.063 --> 00:29:12.243
-Okay.
-Careful.

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:19.722
So, Doc's saying you sit up here.

00:29:20.419 --> 00:29:22.429
That's a nice chair, Doc.

00:29:23.449 --> 00:29:24.855
Quite comfortable chair

00:29:26.081 --> 00:29:27.681
then you just look for wildlife.

00:29:32.288 --> 00:29:34.761
[Doc] I'll see
thousands of deer every year.

00:29:34.761 --> 00:29:35.594
Thousands.

00:29:35.594 --> 00:29:38.202
We may take two or three deer,
and they're always bucks.

00:29:38.202 --> 00:29:40.226
-We don't take any of the does.
-And you eat it?

00:29:40.226 --> 00:29:43.830
Yeah. I have probably 200 pounds
of venison in the freezer in that shed.

00:29:43.830 --> 00:29:46.174
What are property taxes like in Georgia?

00:29:46.174 --> 00:29:50.141
Like to have 100 acres, is that
a super expensive thing to do every year?

00:29:50.141 --> 00:29:52.289
No.
Property tax really isn't that bad here.

00:29:52.289 --> 00:29:53.969
I need to fix that feeder.

00:29:54.630 --> 00:29:56.040
Why is this thing so tipped?

00:29:56.740 --> 00:29:59.232
Because if you're in
a high property tax state,

00:29:59.232 --> 00:30:02.062
just to exist out here,
even if you have no debt

00:30:02.062 --> 00:30:03.661
is going to cost a lot every year.

00:30:03.661 --> 00:30:07.085
Right, and that's the thing.
I mean, a lot of people don't understand,

00:30:07.085 --> 00:30:09.580
just because you live off grid,
your expenses don't stop.

00:30:09.580 --> 00:30:12.188
I mean, did you pay cash for your land,
or do you have a mortgage?

00:30:12.188 --> 00:30:13.845
You have taxes. You have insurance.

00:30:13.845 --> 00:30:15.747
You want to have insurance on your place?

00:30:15.747 --> 00:30:18.406
The expenses don't stop,
and that's one of the things

00:30:18.406 --> 00:30:21.040
I think a lot of people miss
with the off grid lifestyles.

00:30:21.040 --> 00:30:22.618
You still got to have money.

00:30:22.618 --> 00:30:25.357
You want a well?
Where is that 20 grand going to come from?

00:30:25.357 --> 00:30:28.175
You want a tractor?
That tractor is $30,000.

00:30:28.175 --> 00:30:29.819
Where is that money going to come from?

00:30:29.819 --> 00:30:32.670
-You would not have been able
to do this at 25 years old.

00:30:32.670 --> 00:30:33.565
No.

00:30:33.565 --> 00:30:36.166
-It took you working your life
to get to this point.

00:30:36.166 --> 00:30:37.475
Whole life to get to this point.

00:30:37.482 --> 00:30:41.512
Now, what people can do is
they can pull this little pieces out,

00:30:41.755 --> 00:30:45.322
but again,
when we lived in the neighborhood,

00:30:45.762 --> 00:30:47.467
we still did preparation.

00:30:47.468 --> 00:30:49.047
We still did some of that stuff.

00:30:49.047 --> 00:30:49.726
-Yeah.

00:30:49.726 --> 00:30:52.043
But here, this is completely different.

00:30:52.043 --> 00:30:53.193
This takes a checkbook.

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:55.180
[Peter] You have your cameras.

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:58.092
So I have artificial intelligence
that do automatic tracking

00:30:58.092 --> 00:30:59.950
and tell you what is coming across.

00:30:59.950 --> 00:31:01.714
Those artificial intelligence cameras

00:31:01.714 --> 00:31:04.630
will tell you if it's a vehicle,
person, or an animal.

00:31:04.630 --> 00:31:07.845
Those are positioned at my gates
and all around the property.

00:31:07.845 --> 00:31:09.739
These are cellular game cameras

00:31:10.059 --> 00:31:14.012
all throughout the woods,
so I can monitor if there's any predators,

00:31:14.012 --> 00:31:15.456
but mainly for deer movement.

00:31:15.456 --> 00:31:18.305
But if someone comes through my property
in the woods,

00:31:18.305 --> 00:31:19.473
it'll send me a picture.

00:31:19.473 --> 00:31:21.849
I'll get pictures of us riding on our cart.

00:31:27.060 --> 00:31:30.010
[Peter] Do you mind me asking
how much you got this whole place for?

00:31:30.010 --> 00:31:33.179
So the entire property was right at $400.

00:31:33.179 --> 00:31:35.050
-Wow. What year?
-Four years ago.

00:31:35.050 --> 00:31:36.653
-For the whole place?
-The whole place.

00:31:36.653 --> 00:31:39.933
-But it didn't look like this.
-It was a hell hole.

00:31:40.385 --> 00:31:42.506
-But just that amount of land is amazing.

00:31:42.506 --> 00:31:46.416
Yeah. And especially this close to a town
where you're not isolated, you know?

00:31:46.416 --> 00:31:47.443
-Yeah.

00:31:47.443 --> 00:31:48.443
So…

00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:50.624
here, I wanted…

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:54.000
the best way to describe this,
I think, is just country comfortable.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:54.960
-Okay.

00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:58.080
I didn't want to have to
take off my boots when I came in here.

00:31:58.080 --> 00:32:00.394
You go from a field,
you go from hunting, whatever,

00:32:00.394 --> 00:32:02.407
you don't want to walk into a luxury.

00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:06.709
It's nice, but at the same time,
it's country comfortable.

00:32:06.709 --> 00:32:07.709
Very open.

00:32:08.010 --> 00:32:10.263
These beams are probably
one of my favorite.

00:32:10.263 --> 00:32:12.942
We put a mile of shiplap
on all the ceilings,

00:32:12.942 --> 00:32:14.159
but these beams,

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:17.705
these came from a tobacco barn, 1797,

00:32:18.372 --> 00:32:21.334
and this is exactly how
they came out of the barn.

00:32:21.334 --> 00:32:22.420
Just like this.

00:32:22.420 --> 00:32:24.640
And we put them up
just to use 'em, all the seams,

00:32:24.641 --> 00:32:26.340
and I've got them all over.
They're great.

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:28.507
-Oh, you did a great job here.

00:32:28.507 --> 00:32:30.663
-This is beautiful.
-Kitchen area.

00:32:30.663 --> 00:32:32.483
You're always near one,
as you said earlier.

00:32:32.483 --> 00:32:33.593
I'm always near one.

00:32:33.593 --> 00:32:35.964
I'm always within arm's reach of something.

00:32:36.570 --> 00:32:40.499
I was in the Marine Corps,
but I was also criminal investigations

00:32:40.499 --> 00:32:42.061
and did a lot of drug work,

00:32:42.062 --> 00:32:44.600
so I always have something on me.

00:32:45.373 --> 00:32:47.778
This is, I guess now you have to…

00:32:47.779 --> 00:32:50.458
politically, you have to call it
the primary, not the master.

00:32:50.458 --> 00:32:52.399
This was that old nasty garage.

00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:55.356
And then in here, we put this in.

00:32:55.356 --> 00:32:58.280
-This is sort of the bath, the master bath.
-Oh yeah, fantastic.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:00.267
But it's not opulent.

00:33:00.267 --> 00:33:01.490
It's just nice.

00:33:01.490 --> 00:33:03.121
And that's wifey's corner?

00:33:03.121 --> 00:33:05.500
Yeah. That's all wifey's stuff.
I have my own…

00:33:05.501 --> 00:33:07.447
-There's an alarm that goes off
when you walk in?

00:33:07.447 --> 00:33:08.926
Yes. I'm not allowed in there.

00:33:08.926 --> 00:33:11.523
And it's funny because upstairs,

00:33:11.908 --> 00:33:14.500
I have my office
and there's a guest bedroom.

00:33:14.500 --> 00:33:15.600
During hunting season,

00:33:16.134 --> 00:33:18.806
I'll sleep up there half the time
because I wake up at 4:30

00:33:18.806 --> 00:33:21.030
and she and the dogs are like, hm-mm.

00:33:21.030 --> 00:33:22.654
So I'll go sleep upstairs

00:33:23.398 --> 00:33:25.954
so I don't wake them up
at 4:30 in the morning.

00:33:27.370 --> 00:33:30.420
This was a bathroom
and so we didn't have a place for a pantry.

00:33:30.667 --> 00:33:32.960
-So you don't have
any huge rations of food?

00:33:33.259 --> 00:33:34.259
Not here.

00:33:34.990 --> 00:33:37.872
-But on the property somewhere? Okay.
-On the property.

00:33:37.872 --> 00:33:40.553
-And you're saying two years?
-Oh, yeah. Easy.

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:42.893
[Doc] This was disgusting up here.

00:33:43.870 --> 00:33:45.639
There was so much crap up here.

00:33:46.446 --> 00:33:48.764
This is some of my photography, by the way.

00:33:48.764 --> 00:33:49.963
-Oh, beautiful.

00:33:51.306 --> 00:33:53.060
-This is where the magic happens.

00:33:53.060 --> 00:33:54.260
-What are these guns here?

00:33:54.260 --> 00:33:56.063
-These are both just AR frames.

00:33:56.480 --> 00:33:59.065
This one,  a lot of people say,
oh, it's a military…

00:33:59.065 --> 00:34:01.666
I actually hunt with this gun
over here sometimes too.

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:03.310
Just a little plinking gun.

00:34:03.658 --> 00:34:05.465
And this is actually… I mean, this is…

00:34:05.465 --> 00:34:06.465
In our area,

00:34:06.837 --> 00:34:08.582
most people have a plinker,

00:34:08.582 --> 00:34:11.631
a long bolt gun for deer hunting,

00:34:11.632 --> 00:34:12.679
and handguns.

00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:15.739
It's just normal. All these deer
came from this property here.

00:34:15.739 --> 00:34:18.539
-Georgia is a pro-gun-friendly state?
-Oh, absolutely.

00:34:18.539 --> 00:34:22.916
You can't go to a property here
and not have people own guns.

00:34:22.916 --> 00:34:24.960
Now, the mistake that some people make…

00:34:25.410 --> 00:34:29.315
I know people that buy guns,
and guns, and guns, and guns, and guns.

00:34:29.315 --> 00:34:30.390
That's not me.

00:34:30.390 --> 00:34:31.708
I just have what I use.

00:34:32.090 --> 00:34:36.245
And they put too much money into their guns
and there's no other infrastructure around.

00:34:36.245 --> 00:34:37.245
Huge mistake.

00:34:37.245 --> 00:34:39.497
-You have the infrastructure?
-I have the infrastructure.

00:34:39.497 --> 00:34:41.445
-And a lot you can't talk about.
-Right.

00:34:41.445 --> 00:34:43.145
I won't talk about yet. [chuckles]

00:34:44.353 --> 00:34:47.380
So, do you think that helps
with home invasions?

00:34:47.673 --> 00:34:50.023
When you're in a place like this,
rural Georgia.

00:34:50.454 --> 00:34:52.713
-Everyone knows everyone has guns.
-Yes.

00:34:52.713 --> 00:34:54.821
Does it make you think twice?

00:34:54.821 --> 00:34:56.489
If you go to my gate,

00:34:56.489 --> 00:34:59.057
my wife is like, oh, we need to do
something fancier on that.

00:34:59.057 --> 00:35:02.412
I said, look. I want to make it
look like a redneck with a gun

00:35:02.412 --> 00:35:04.120
lives at the end of this driveway.

00:35:04.120 --> 00:35:06.520
And if you come down
this driveway 900 feet…

00:35:07.690 --> 00:35:09.601
-But you sort of are Doc.
-Yeah.

00:35:09.601 --> 00:35:12.020
You have a redneck ethos.

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:14.046
Embrace it. [laughs]

00:35:14.749 --> 00:35:17.314
So, the whole point is,

00:35:17.314 --> 00:35:19.230
people do not pull down my driveway.

00:35:19.230 --> 00:35:22.336
'Cause they know in this area,
if you come down this driveway,

00:35:22.336 --> 00:35:24.302
there's going to be someone
with a gun at the end.

00:35:24.302 --> 00:35:26.232
Now, that's true for all my neighbors.
I mean…

00:35:26.233 --> 00:35:28.666
So, you'd say property crime is low here?

00:35:28.972 --> 00:35:29.972
I…

00:35:30.758 --> 00:35:31.880
I'll tell you this.

00:35:31.880 --> 00:35:35.630
My wallet and my keys have never left
my truck, and my truck's never locked.

00:35:36.130 --> 00:35:38.762
-This is where Doc runs his operations.
-That's the magic happens.

00:35:38.762 --> 00:35:41.216
The magic happens looking out at the pond

00:35:41.216 --> 00:35:43.703
saying, I gotta finish up on this project.

00:35:43.703 --> 00:35:46.180
-And then I'm going fishing.
-[Doc chuckles]

00:35:46.180 --> 00:35:49.656
And at least twice a day,
I go fishing just to relax.

00:35:50.080 --> 00:35:52.657
But a lot of people ask…
Here's a good example.

00:35:53.165 --> 00:35:54.295
A lot of people ask,

00:35:54.296 --> 00:35:57.570
"Hey, you got such a nice house,
why do you have window units?"

00:35:57.570 --> 00:36:00.586
If you've ever been in a hurricane
with a power outage,

00:36:00.586 --> 00:36:04.458
and you want to run,
you can actually shut off all your HVAC,

00:36:04.766 --> 00:36:07.788
close your bedroom door,
have it freezing cold,

00:36:07.788 --> 00:36:10.988
and this thing only pulls 700 watts.

00:36:10.988 --> 00:36:14.215
-Okay. So, you can compartmentalize
in a home, right?

00:36:14.215 --> 00:36:16.416
When these catastrophes happen?

00:36:16.416 --> 00:36:17.416
-Absolutely.

00:36:17.416 --> 00:36:20.230
-So, you could just move it to your office.
-Yep.

00:36:20.230 --> 00:36:22.586
-And there's a guest bedroom.
-Guest bedroom.

00:36:22.586 --> 00:36:25.086
Another bath.
So, we've got two full baths up here.

00:36:26.392 --> 00:36:27.998
Stay to the right.

00:36:27.998 --> 00:36:30.396
I can't believe the inspector
allowed these stairs.

00:36:30.396 --> 00:36:33.731
We were allowed to keep them,
'cause they don't really meet code.

00:36:33.731 --> 00:36:36.793
What we can do,
we'll actually take the property off grid.

00:36:37.140 --> 00:36:39.890
Let's go out here first.
Let me show you how this works.

00:36:41.387 --> 00:36:42.876
Big battery bank over here.

00:36:42.876 --> 00:36:45.382
Big underground cable comes in over here.

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:48.088
This is an A-B switch.

00:36:48.750 --> 00:36:52.075
So, I am on the grid, so it's off.

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:55.073
If I go down I'm on the battery system.

00:36:55.073 --> 00:36:56.073
If I go up,

00:36:58.899 --> 00:37:00.870
try to stick your camera in there,

00:37:00.870 --> 00:37:02.170
then I go on my generator.

00:37:02.769 --> 00:37:04.895
So this is a generator
that'll run the whole house

00:37:04.895 --> 00:37:06.616
if I want to go gas generator.

00:37:06.616 --> 00:37:09.380
-So, you can go solar, gas, or on grid.

00:37:09.380 --> 00:37:11.101
-You have three ways?
-Yeah.

00:37:11.578 --> 00:37:12.881
So, and the other thing is…

00:37:12.881 --> 00:37:14.840
-That's in case the solar doesn't work?

00:37:14.840 --> 00:37:17.215
Something happens maybe or

00:37:17.696 --> 00:37:20.069
the nice thing about this is
this power goes into the house,

00:37:20.069 --> 00:37:24.340
which goes back over there so I can
charge my batteries while this is running.

00:37:24.340 --> 00:37:28.786
So, if I have a snowstorm or whatever…
you know, it's going.

00:37:28.786 --> 00:37:32.679
But right now we're on gas generator.

00:37:32.679 --> 00:37:33.679
We're off.

00:37:33.679 --> 00:37:36.053
-[switch clanks]
-I'm going to hook up the EcoFlow system.

00:37:36.053 --> 00:37:38.668
And then we'll go in,
and we'll just throw it online.

00:37:38.668 --> 00:37:39.807
I've got everything running.

00:37:39.807 --> 00:37:42.592
I've got the fountains running,
the aerators, all the lights.

00:37:42.593 --> 00:37:43.649
Everything on.

00:37:44.630 --> 00:37:46.822
-This is sort of your moment, right, Doc?

00:37:46.822 --> 00:37:50.410
When you flip that switch,
and you're like, all my work…

00:37:50.707 --> 00:37:54.345
We had
40 or 50 mile an hour winds out here.

00:37:54.345 --> 00:37:57.895
Two years ago, we had a thunderstorm
come through, and we lost 21 trees.

00:37:58.770 --> 00:38:01.370
We couldn't even get out.
We lost power for two days.

00:38:01.370 --> 00:38:03.338
And we did not have this system in place.

00:38:03.338 --> 00:38:04.538
We just had a generator.

00:38:05.340 --> 00:38:07.454
So, we're hooked up in here now.

00:38:07.810 --> 00:38:09.846
And so, all I've got to do is come in here.

00:38:10.382 --> 00:38:12.462
And I have to…

00:38:12.462 --> 00:38:16.102
This is the setup that everyone…
This is called an interlock switch.

00:38:16.523 --> 00:38:18.549
This is what you have
when you have a generator.

00:38:18.549 --> 00:38:22.280
You have to kill the main power
then you can turn this over,

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:24.640
and then you can turn your generator on.

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:29.400
So the reason why you do this is
if you're throwing power back to the grid,

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:32.573
and the lineman comes to work on it,
you'll end up killing them.

00:38:33.070 --> 00:38:36.138
So, that's why
you have to have this by code.

00:38:36.510 --> 00:38:38.338
-This shuts off the main.
-[switch clunks]

00:38:38.338 --> 00:38:39.520
We're off.

00:38:39.520 --> 00:38:40.587
So, now…

00:38:40.587 --> 00:38:41.587
[beeping]

00:38:42.290 --> 00:38:44.690
This is my app that controls that.

00:38:44.690 --> 00:38:48.057
And the one thing I forgot to do
is I forgot to turn the AC power on.

00:38:48.057 --> 00:38:50.376
So, that's why, when I switched it over…

00:38:50.376 --> 00:38:54.235
So, now what I'm going to do
is I'm going to turn the AC power on.

00:38:55.130 --> 00:38:57.479
So, it's communicating
to that system over there.

00:38:58.295 --> 00:39:02.230
And what it will do now is it will show me
how much power is being taken out,

00:39:02.230 --> 00:39:04.745
plus how much
is being fed in by the solar panels.

00:39:05.260 --> 00:39:08.915
So right now on the solar panels,
I have about 2,400 watts going in.

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:11.655
And what's the wattage coming out?

00:39:13.006 --> 00:39:15.248
About 2,300 watts

00:39:16.061 --> 00:39:17.460
being used by the house.

00:39:17.460 --> 00:39:19.320
So, we're all completely off grid.

00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:23.250
Without even the solar that system
will run this house for two full days.

00:39:23.675 --> 00:39:25.500
-Or more.
-Just off the battery power?

00:39:25.500 --> 00:39:28.305
Just off the battery.
And if you're conservative, which is…

00:39:28.305 --> 00:39:31.055
In my videos I talk about
something called a Miser Mode.

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:35.043
Turn off your hot water heater,
turn off your ac, turn off the big stuff.

00:39:35.650 --> 00:39:37.842
Wi-Fi, lights, little basic stuff.

00:39:37.842 --> 00:39:40.190
You can run
probably four days off that battery.

00:39:40.190 --> 00:39:43.190
Why are you making videos
on this topic, Doc?

00:39:43.190 --> 00:39:44.713
I've done it for years.

00:39:44.713 --> 00:39:48.538
I've always sort of touched on it
but now I do a lot of testing.

00:39:48.538 --> 00:39:50.430
I have different levels of it.

00:39:50.430 --> 00:39:54.439
Like the $1,600, the $100.

00:39:54.439 --> 00:39:57.956
Right. On your channel,
I've talked more about the lifestyle.

00:39:57.956 --> 00:40:01.122
On your channel, you go very granular
on the technicality of things.

00:40:01.122 --> 00:40:05.180
So for someone wanting to do this,
they would go to your channel.

00:40:05.180 --> 00:40:07.330
Right. And pick up some of the videos.

00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:09.240
I don't try and be an expert on it.

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:12.405
I sort of show you what I'm living with
and what I've learned.

00:40:12.405 --> 00:40:14.232
-I'm sure a lot of trial and error.

00:40:14.232 --> 00:40:15.353
Yes. Huge amount.

00:40:16.300 --> 00:40:19.900
If you want to be great at something,
screw it up a whole bunch of times.

00:40:19.900 --> 00:40:20.900
[chuckling]

00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:24.830
-Okay, Doc, so most people
are not gonna be able to do this.

00:40:24.830 --> 00:40:26.510
A, not have the money.

00:40:26.510 --> 00:40:27.920
B, not have the time.

00:40:27.920 --> 00:40:29.600
C, not have the skills.

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:30.930
They're not super handy.

00:40:30.930 --> 00:40:33.390
It's going to be a ton of work
they don't want to do.

00:40:33.390 --> 00:40:36.432
But you're saying almost everyone
can have some preparation.

00:40:36.432 --> 00:40:37.470
Everyone.

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:38.493
And this is your kit?

00:40:38.493 --> 00:40:42.177
If I was king for a day, I would mandate
that everyone had seven days.

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:44.878
Down at the beach house,
I have one of these containers

00:40:44.879 --> 00:40:45.864
and a small generator.

00:40:45.864 --> 00:40:47.790
-Beach house in Georgia?
-Yes.

00:40:47.790 --> 00:40:50.527
I have one of these containers
and a small generator and that's it.

00:40:50.527 --> 00:40:53.153
So, if we have a hurricane,
have one of these.

00:40:53.153 --> 00:40:54.360
Now, these get heavy.

00:40:54.360 --> 00:40:57.450
So, I recommend you get
one of these totes with wheels.

00:40:57.450 --> 00:40:59.170
-So, this is seven days?

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:01.530
Actually, 14 really you could do.

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:04.990
I'm highly interested 'cause I'm not
gonna do what you've done today.

00:41:04.990 --> 00:41:08.220
I'm out there making videos. Busy.
Don't have time for any of this stuff.

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:09.878
-Everyone should do this.
-Okay.

00:41:10.236 --> 00:41:11.408
And this,

00:41:12.098 --> 00:41:15.190
I didn't load it up
with 14 days' worth of stuff.

00:41:15.190 --> 00:41:17.841
I just loaded up with examples
of stuff that you can do.

00:41:17.841 --> 00:41:19.801
This is just simple stuff.
You go to Lowe's.

00:41:19.801 --> 00:41:22.275
I mean, you go to Walmart,
Costco, whatever.

00:41:22.275 --> 00:41:25.661
And see, the mistake people make
is they think that you got to buy in bulk

00:41:25.661 --> 00:41:28.557
and then you got to vacuum seal,
you got to use oxygen packets.

00:41:29.073 --> 00:41:30.321
It's just not true.

00:41:30.583 --> 00:41:31.630
You can buy…

00:41:31.630 --> 00:41:36.172
I actually prefer to buy small stuff
like little bags of rice, pasta.

00:41:36.512 --> 00:41:37.512
Little things.

00:41:37.750 --> 00:41:39.130
And it'll last for years.

00:41:39.130 --> 00:41:41.180
People think that it doesn't, but it does.

00:41:41.180 --> 00:41:44.940
So, as an example, I'mma
start throwing some stuff out at you.

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:45.940
Okay. What's this?

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:48.233
Emergency radio.
You can crank it, put it in solar.

00:41:48.990 --> 00:41:51.475
This is the most amazing little thing
that you'll ever see.

00:41:51.475 --> 00:41:54.287
That little stove runs off gasoline.

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:55.836
So, you take gasoline.

00:41:55.836 --> 00:41:58.463
You have a can of gasoline in the house,
everyone does.

00:41:58.463 --> 00:41:59.722
You can actually cook on that.

00:41:59.722 --> 00:42:01.648
Besides your gas grill or whatever.

00:42:01.648 --> 00:42:04.754
-Okay. You're in an apartment.
You don't have gasoline kicking around.

00:42:04.754 --> 00:42:06.507
-Then…
-Propane?

00:42:06.507 --> 00:42:08.813
-Go propane canisters.
-Yeah, you can have propane.

00:42:08.813 --> 00:42:13.380
This is that little $100 backup system
I talked about right there.

00:42:13.380 --> 00:42:14.380
So, this is…

00:42:15.373 --> 00:42:16.623
You can plug in a laptop.

00:42:17.286 --> 00:42:18.779
You've got USB charging.

00:42:19.330 --> 00:42:21.328
It actually has
flashlights on as well too.

00:42:21.328 --> 00:42:23.460
But it also comes with a solar panel.

00:42:23.460 --> 00:42:26.209
You open up the solar panel,
you charge this with the sun.

00:42:26.209 --> 00:42:27.329
-Okay.
-Really cool.

00:42:28.675 --> 00:42:31.370
-Most amazing product ever.
-What? Wipes?

00:42:31.370 --> 00:42:33.297
Dude Wipes instead of toilet paper.

00:42:33.297 --> 00:42:34.875
-You don't like toilet paper?
-Dude.

00:42:35.309 --> 00:42:37.623
Once you try these,
you'll never go back. Trust me.

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:40.031
So, the Dude Wipes are high on the list.

00:42:40.031 --> 00:42:41.760
-Didn't see that coming.
-Yeah.

00:42:42.065 --> 00:42:44.706
This is a little water purification thing.

00:42:46.183 --> 00:42:48.093
So, you can actually take pond water,

00:42:48.094 --> 00:42:51.492
run it through the system
and it'll remove 99% of everything

00:42:51.912 --> 00:42:54.062
including micros
and all that kind of stuff.

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:56.410
People don't think about lighters.

00:42:56.410 --> 00:42:58.993
If you need a lighter,
people sometimes don't have lighters.

00:42:58.993 --> 00:43:01.839
I don't smoke,
so you've got to have a lighter in here.

00:43:01.839 --> 00:43:04.739
One of the biggest things
during Hurricane Helene was this.

00:43:05.454 --> 00:43:06.454
Cash.

00:43:07.100 --> 00:43:09.821
All the stores are down, the Wi-Fi is down.
Sorry, it's cash only.

00:43:09.821 --> 00:43:13.124
There's a guy named Jeff Gray on YouTube,

00:43:13.124 --> 00:43:16.317
and I've actually talked to him
and stole some of his video.

00:43:16.603 --> 00:43:20.633
He was in line at a store
and people were crying

00:43:20.633 --> 00:43:23.560
because they couldn't buy
what they needed because it was cash only.

00:43:23.560 --> 00:43:25.150
They didn't have cash.

00:43:25.150 --> 00:43:26.549
Fives, tens, and twenties.

00:43:26.860 --> 00:43:28.927
-Get a bag of it, stick it in here.
-How much cash?

00:43:28.928 --> 00:43:30.580
More the better, obviously.

00:43:30.580 --> 00:43:32.416
Yeah, a hundred, two hundred bucks maybe.

00:43:32.417 --> 00:43:34.588
Just throw it in here
and just forget about it.

00:43:34.588 --> 00:43:35.981
Just don't worry about it.

00:43:35.982 --> 00:43:37.530
Cash is absolutely critical.

00:43:37.530 --> 00:43:39.920
Here's where you can have fun with this
if you have kids.

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:41.270
Have the kids participate.

00:43:41.270 --> 00:43:43.850
Say, this is gonna be
one of our insurance boxes.

00:43:43.850 --> 00:43:46.659
If we have a bad storm
and the power goes out,

00:43:46.660 --> 00:43:49.620
you guys get to pick what you want
so you can put something in here.

00:43:49.620 --> 00:43:50.918
The kids get excited about it.

00:43:50.918 --> 00:43:53.906
So anytime, trust me,
if you have kids and a storm comes up,

00:43:53.906 --> 00:43:56.034
they'll be like, "Can we get the box out?"

00:43:56.034 --> 00:43:58.080
Because, you know, you're going to have…

00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:00.330
Especially with young kids,

00:44:00.837 --> 00:44:02.460
you know, coloring books and crayons.

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:05.650
So, you know, you can't touch this
unless the power goes out or whatever.

00:44:05.650 --> 00:44:09.995
So you take a bad situation,
a hurricane, power loss, or whatever,

00:44:09.995 --> 00:44:12.729
and the kids get excited about it
because they know they're prepared.

00:44:12.729 --> 00:44:14.923
Plus, they feel secure,
which is kind of nice.

00:44:15.495 --> 00:44:16.495
[Peter] Okay, food.

00:44:16.999 --> 00:44:17.999
-Okay.

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:20.040
-Quaker Oats.

00:44:22.673 --> 00:44:24.526
[Doc] I can't live without coffee.

00:44:24.526 --> 00:44:25.739
-Coffee.

00:44:25.739 --> 00:44:27.120
And you bag it all up.

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:28.793
-Some of it, like Bisquick.

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:31.279
Bisquick has a shelf life instead of flour.

00:44:31.279 --> 00:44:34.460
Bisquick in a box has a shelf life
of one and a half years.

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:36.946
If you take it out and shrink wrap it,
you're about four years.

00:44:36.946 --> 00:44:39.090
-Not the healthiest,
but it's going to survive.

00:44:39.090 --> 00:44:41.236
-If you need to cook.
-Okay.

00:44:41.611 --> 00:44:44.264
Crunchy granola bars,
if you shrink wrap it like this,

00:44:44.458 --> 00:44:47.653
I'm telling you five years down the road
you can pull that out and eat it.

00:44:48.246 --> 00:44:49.472
Here's a perfect example.

00:44:50.099 --> 00:44:52.299
Instead of buying 50-pound bags of rice,

00:44:52.742 --> 00:44:54.559
buy these are already in plastic.

00:44:55.026 --> 00:44:57.939
Same thing with pasta.
You can get pasta that's in plastic.

00:44:57.939 --> 00:45:00.866
We did a test.
We put this in a cabinet for four years,

00:45:01.117 --> 00:45:04.032
pulled it out, and ate it just like this,
and it was perfect.

00:45:04.032 --> 00:45:05.010
Four years later.

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:07.053
People think you have to do
special preparations.

00:45:07.053 --> 00:45:08.151
You really don't.

00:45:08.151 --> 00:45:10.206
Buy it in plastic, put it in a plastic bag.

00:45:11.490 --> 00:45:13.641
But there's just
all kinds of stuff in here.

00:45:13.641 --> 00:45:15.915
-Okay. So just have enough food rations.

00:45:15.915 --> 00:45:18.520
We're talking two weeks
if you have this filled right.

00:45:18.520 --> 00:45:20.865
Two weeks is all sitting right here.

00:45:20.865 --> 00:45:22.070
-What about water?

00:45:22.070 --> 00:45:24.160
Water,
you're gonna have to do that separately.

00:45:24.160 --> 00:45:25.486
-You got your pump, but…

00:45:25.486 --> 00:45:27.106
Yeah. You're going to have to have…

00:45:27.106 --> 00:45:30.624
They make something called
a water bob, which fills the bathtub.

00:45:31.272 --> 00:45:33.241
-Then you get a bunch of canned stuff.

00:45:33.241 --> 00:45:36.416
And you got oils.
And then my favorite, I love Wendy's chili.

00:45:36.416 --> 00:45:37.416
But you take rice,

00:45:38.018 --> 00:45:40.756
throw some beef stew
on the rice or on the pasta,

00:45:40.757 --> 00:45:42.690
chili, put it on the rice and pasta.

00:45:42.690 --> 00:45:43.840
Simple stuff, you know?

00:45:47.242 --> 00:45:49.250
One of the things I like to tell people is,

00:45:49.250 --> 00:45:52.700
first, understand the difference
between a black swan and a gray swan.

00:45:53.230 --> 00:45:56.600
A black swan is something
like 9-11 and COVID.

00:45:57.040 --> 00:45:59.120
It's something that
you didn't think would happen,

00:45:59.121 --> 00:46:00.800
something you're not prepared for,

00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:03.150
something that just
catches you by surprise.

00:46:03.150 --> 00:46:05.416
A gray swan is something that

00:46:05.417 --> 00:46:08.512
everyone knows could happen,
but you sort of blow it off

00:46:08.512 --> 00:46:10.718
because you don't think
it's really gonna happen.

00:46:10.725 --> 00:46:13.385
And that's more of like the economy,

00:46:13.785 --> 00:46:15.480
housing collapse, whatever.

00:46:15.480 --> 00:46:17.500
And a perfect example, and I'll use this.

00:46:17.500 --> 00:46:19.150
I like to use this as an example.

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:21.439
In 1855,

00:46:22.138 --> 00:46:25.520
that right there, was worth 20 bucks.

00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:27.418
If you adjust it for inflation,

00:46:28.126 --> 00:46:30.432
